You're likely to be rated as more attractive when pictured in a group than when alone, according to new research.

Being pictured with friends could boost your perceived attractiveness as people tend to 'average out' everyone's facial features when looking at group photos.

Observers perceive each individual's face as
 more average than they would otherwise - and average faces are deemed more attractive. The phenomenon is dubbed the 'cheerleader effect'.

